%I A396948 #20 Jun 16 2026 00:05:11
%S A396948 10,15,18,20,30,40,45,50,60,70,80,90,100,110,120,130,140,150,160,170,
%T A396948 180,190,200,210,220,230,240,250,260,270,280,290,300,310,320,330,340,
%U A396948 350,360,370,380,390,400,410,420,430,440,450,460,470,480,490,500,510,520,530,540,550,560
%N A396948 Numbers m with two or more digits such that if we insert a 0 between the units and tens digits we get a multiple of the original number.
%C A396948 This sequence is the answer to the problem 1 of the 17th Mexican Mathematical Olympiad in 2003 (see link).
%C A396948 Solve the Diophantine equation: 100*b + u = k * (10*b + u) <==> 10 * (10-k) * u = (k-1) * b, where u is the units digit, gives solutions.
%H A396948 Michael S. Branicky, <a href="/A396948/b396948.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10003</a> (all terms <= 10^5)
%H A396948 Kalva, <a href="https://webee.technion.ac.il/people/aditya/www.kalva.demon.co.uk/mexico/mex03.html">17th Mexican Mathematical Olympiad, problem 1, 2003</a>.
%H A396948 <a href="/index/O#Olympiads">Index to sequences related to Olympiads</a>.
%F A396948 Equals {15, 18, 45} U {10*m, m >= 1}.
%e A396948 18 is a term since 108 / 18 = 6.
%e A396948 45 is a term since 405 / 45 = 9.
%t A396948 Select[Range[10,560],Divisible[Floor[#/10]*100+Mod[#,10],#] &] (* _Stefano Spezia_, Jun 11 2026 *)
%o A396948 (Python)
%o A396948 def ok(m):
%o A396948     if m < 10: return False
%o A396948     q, r = divmod(m, 10)
%o A396948     return (q*100+r)%m == 0
%o A396948 print([m for m in range(600) if ok(m)]) # _Michael S. Branicky_, Jun 11 2026
%Y A396948 Cf. A285176, A008592 \ {0} (subsequences).
%Y A396948 Cf. A343550.
%K A396948 nonn,base,new
%O A396948 1,1
